  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's climate gives a backyard pool genuine year-round value in a way that pools in Sydney, Melbourne, or Adelaide rarely achieve. With a typical swim season of eight to nine months in the inner east (and longer if heated), a well-maintained pool is a lifestyle asset that families actively use, not a feature that sits cold for most of the year. That lifestyle reality flows directly through to how buyers perceive a pool at sale, and to the price the property achieves. This article is about the practical economics of pool ownership for Brisbane sellers: what a pool typically costs to run, what it adds to a sale, what buyers actually worry about, and what to do in the weeks before listing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a pool typically adds to value at sale</h2>
      <p>For family-oriented inner-east suburbs, a well-presented in-ground pool typically adds in the order of five to eight per cent to a property's sale value, with the upper end of that range reserved for pools that are properly integrated with the outdoor living area, well maintained, and visibly in good condition. The number is meaningful: on a $1.4m family home in Camp Hill or Hawthorne, that range translates to $70,000 to $112,000 of value. Above-ground pools add comparatively little, and in some cases register as a slight negative because they read as a temporary structure, complicate the use of the yard, and present poorly in marketing photography. The value uplift depends heavily on three things: the quality of the original installation, how well the pool integrates with the outdoor entertaining area, and the apparent maintenance condition at the time of sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a pool typically costs the owner each year</h2>
      <p>Sellers and buyers both ask about ongoing cost, and the realistic numbers help frame the conversation. For a typical Brisbane in-ground pool, annual operating cost in 2028 dollars sits roughly as follows. Chemicals (chlorine or salt for salt-chlorinated systems, acid, stabiliser, and consumables) run $600 to $1,200 per year depending on pool size and how aggressively the chemistry is maintained. Electricity for the pump and any heater runs $1,000 to $2,500 per year, with the upper end reflecting heat pump use through winter. Professional servicing if the owner uses a pool service for a fortnightly visit runs $1,800 to $4,000 per year. Annual repairs and equipment replacements (chlorinator cell, pump components, filter media, tile and grout work, lighting) average $400 to $1,000 per year across a long ownership period. The total realistic annual operating cost for a typical inner-east family pool, properly maintained, sits between $4,000 and $8,000 per year, with feature-heavy installations or heated pools running higher.</p>

      <p>This is not a small number, and buyers do think about it. Sellers who are open about realistic operating cost (rather than minimising it) tend to build trust faster with serious buyers, who have usually already done their own research on pool running costs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually worry about</h2>
      <p>The four concerns that come up most often from buyers inspecting a property with a pool are: the ongoing cost of running and maintaining it, the safety certificate compliance position, the visible condition of the pool at inspection (algae, broken tiles, debris, neglected coping, non-functional lighting), and the proximity of the pool to indoor living areas (noise from the pump, splash zones, sight lines from kitchens and family rooms). The first two are addressed by clear documentation and a current pool safety certificate. The third is addressed by pre-listing presentation. The fourth is structural and cannot be changed, but can be framed in marketing through landscaping cues, screening, and the way the outdoor flow is described.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Buyer profiles by pool preference</h2>
      <p>Different buyer cohorts respond to pools quite differently, and understanding which buyer pool your property is actually targeting matters more than a general view about pools. Families with school-age children strongly value pools, particularly in family-oriented inner-east suburbs where backyard summers are central to lifestyle. Downsizers and older buyers typically prefer no pool, treating it as a maintenance burden they have explicitly moved past. Investor buyers are neutral to slightly negative, reflecting the additional maintenance complications across a tenancy and the safety compliance obligations that the landlord carries. Younger buyers without children are variable, with the pool sometimes adding lifestyle appeal (entertaining, outdoor living) and sometimes registering as cost overhead they would rather avoid. The right read depends on the actual buyer pool for your suburb and price band, not on a general assumption.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do before listing</h2>
      <p>The pre-listing pool work that consistently produces the strongest return is straightforward. Ensure the Pool Safety Certificate is current and on file (a non-compliant fence found at contract stage gives the buyer leverage and slows settlement). Have the pool professionally serviced two to three weeks before the first inspection, with a chemistry reset, surface and tile clean, equipment inspection, and any minor repairs completed. Address visible issues directly: clean tiles and grout, replace damaged coping, fix non-functional lighting, ensure the pump and heater are operational and quiet. Tidy the equipment area so the pump shed or enclosure looks orderly rather than neglected. The total spend on this is typically a few hundred to low thousands of dollars and reliably pays back several multiples in buyer perception and price flexibility.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The staging and photography approach</h2>
      <p>The pool is one of the highest-impact features in the marketing photo set if it is photographed well. Pool areas should be shot in optimal conditions: a sunny day, late afternoon light when possible, the water clear and at the correct level, the surrounds tidy, outdoor furniture in place, and any styling props (towels, plants, drinkware, cushions) extending the lifestyle cue. Twilight shots with the pool lit are particularly strong for marketing campaigns and should be part of the photography brief if the lighting is in good working order. The pool should never be photographed when looking neglected, when the chemistry is off (cloudy water), or under overcast winter light that strips the lifestyle appeal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Saltwater versus chlorinated systems</h2>
      <p>Brisbane pools split between traditional chlorinated systems and salt-chlorinated systems (where a chlorinator cell converts salt to chlorine in the water). Saltwater systems are generally perceived by buyers as gentler on skin and eyes, lower ongoing maintenance, and modern. Chlorinated systems are simpler to repair, have shorter equipment lifecycle on the chlorinator side, and are still common in older installations. Both are acceptable to most buyers; the relevant point for marketing is that the system type and condition should be clearly communicated, and that any visibly aged equipment (an end-of-life chlorinator cell, a pump approaching replacement) should ideally be addressed before listing rather than left as a buyer-side concern.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do</h2>
      <p>The avoidable mistakes are simple and common. Do not present a green or visibly poorly maintained pool, because buyers price in five to fifteen thousand dollars of restoration cost regardless of whether that is the actual repair number. Do not photograph pools in winter when the water looks unused, the surrounds are bare, and the lifestyle cue is absent. Do not omit the pool from marketing photography hoping buyers will not notice; they will know there is a pool from the inspection, and the omission reads as the seller hiding a problem. Do not minimise running costs in conversation with buyers who have done their research; honesty produces stronger trust than an obviously low number.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Pool Safety Certificate as disclosure</h2>
      <p>The Queensland Pool Safety Certificate is the formal compliance document that confirms the pool barrier (fencing, gates, climbable items, surrounds) meets current standards. For a property sale, the certificate is a critical disclosure document. A current certificate at the time of listing is the strongest position. Where the pool is not currently certified, the regime allows the buyer to take responsibility for compliance within a defined period after settlement, but the absence of a certificate weakens the seller's negotiating position and tends to flow into price. Sellers should book a pool safety inspection well before listing rather than discovering rectification work at the contract stage.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>The summary position is straightforward. A well-maintained, well-presented pool in a family-oriented Brisbane suburb is a strong selling feature that adds meaningful value at sale. A poorly presented pool is a meaningful negative that pulls offers down and gives buyers leverage in negotiation. The gap between the two is reliably $20,000 to $50,000 in sale price for typical inner-east family homes, and can be larger for higher-priced properties where the buyer pool is even more discerning. Pre-listing investment in a chemistry reset, professional service, minor repairs, current safety certificate, and good photography is one of the highest-return small expenditures sellers can make. The economics consistently favour spending the few thousand dollars to present the pool well rather than leaving it as a buyer-side discount item in negotiation.</p>

